tablify.py - Table String Formatter

Version 0.1.3

tablify allows users to store a formatted text table in memory and print it.


Example Usage:

import tablify

t = tablify.Table(header=('Food', 'Proteins', 'Fats', 'Carbs', 'Calories', 'Notes'))
t.writeline(['Meat', '25', '12', '5', '40', 'The Best'])
t.writeline(('Cheese', '14', '5', '5', '20', 'Also Good!'))
t.writeline("Soy,l,0,s,3r,YUCK")
t.writeline(['Aliens', '?'])

print(t.stringify())


------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Food       | Proteins   | Fats       | Carbs      | Calories   | Notes      
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Meat       | 25         | 12         | 5          | 40         | The Best   
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Cheese     | 14         | 5          | 5          | 20         | Also Good! 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Soy        | l          | 0          | s          | 3r         | YUCK       
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
| Aliens     | ?          |            |            |            |            



In its core, tablify is a wrapper for the python String .format() method. It creates the template string later used with format()
Formatting is generated by the helper Formatter Class. If not specified tablify will use a default Formatter object with premade settings


